          "title": "Micah's lament and the logic of idolatry",
          "body": "When Micah catches up with the Danites and demands his gods back, his words carry an unintentional theological precision: 'You have taken away my gods which **I made**, and the priest, and have gone away; and what do I have besides?' (18:24). He made them. He funded them. He hired the priest to service them. And now he is bereft because they are gone — he has nothing besides. The lament exposes the inner logic of idolatry with surgical clarity. A god you make is a god you own; a god you own is a god you can lose; a god you can lose leaves you with nothing. Calvin writes in the Institutes that the human heart is a perpetual factory of idols — but the factory forgets that manufactured gods cannot protect their manufacturer. Micah's gods did not defend themselves from theft, cannot pursue the thieves, and will not return to him. The very helplessness that made Laish vulnerable to Dan's army also characterizes Micah's gods: they are quiet, unsuspecting, and unable to deliver anyone. The narrator places Micah's lament immediately after the Levite's gladness, and the juxtaposition is devastating — both men are equally undone by the same worthless objects."
