          "title": "The institutionalization of apostasy",
          "body": "Judges 18 does not end with the conquest of Laish. It ends with a dynastic founding. The sons of Dan set up the graven image; Jonathan son of Gershom son of Moses became the founding priest; his sons served 'until the day of the captivity of the land' (18:30). Two details in verse 30 demand attention. First, the name: Jonathan son of Gershom son of Moses. The ancient scribal tradition (preserved in a suspended nun in the Hebrew text at 18:30) reflects later copyists' reluctance to attach Moses' name to this genealogy — some manuscripts read 'Manasseh' to distance the lawgiver from the lawbreaker. Whether Moses or Manasseh, the genealogy traces the apostate priest to the very man who received the law at Sinai. Second, the duration: 'until the day of the captivity.' The Dan shrine endures for centuries, later becoming one of Jeroboam's two golden-calf sanctuaries (1 Kings 12:29-30), and the dynasty of priests who serve it stretches from the judges period to the Assyrian destruction of 722 BC. Individual sin becomes family practice becomes tribal religion becomes national policy. This is how apostasy works — not in dramatic catastrophic collapses but in institutional normalizations, each generation inheriting what the last generation built, until what was once a scandal is simply 'how we worship here.'"
