          "title": "The silence of God and the sovereignty of his judgment",
          "body": "One of the most theologically weighty features of Judges 18 is what it does not contain: a divine speech, a divine rebuke, a divine intervention. God does not appear in this chapter. He is mentioned by name only in the Levite's unauthorized oracle (18:6) and in the spies' recruitment speech (18:10) — both uses of the divine name are human projections onto God's silence. The narrator does not insert the standard Deuteronomistic formula ('and this was evil in the sight of the LORD'); he does not send a prophet; he does not dispatch an angel. He simply records. This silence is itself a form of judgment — what theologians following Romans 1:24-28 call the wrath of abandonment. God has given Dan over to the desires its tribal assembly chose. Jonathan Edwards noted in his sermons on Judges that the most fearful divine judgment in Scripture is not fire from heaven but heaven's withdrawal from a people who have systematically preferred their own religious constructions to the God who gave them His law. Laish burns, an unauthorized shrine is founded, a Mosaic descendant serves graven images, and heaven is quiet. The house of God is at Shiloh (18:31). Nobody from Dan goes there."
